What is the structure of your dataset?¶

  • The dataset contains 183,412 Ford GoBike trips from February to March 2019 and 16 features about each trip. Each trip is described by the following:duration_sec, start_time, end_time, start_station_id, start_station_name, start_station_latitude, start_station_longitude, end_station_id, end_station_name, end_station_latitude, end_station_longitude, bike_id, user_type, member_birth_year, member_gender, bike_share_for_all_trip.
  • The columns types are mostly numerical with two date format columns (start time and end time), three nominal categroical columns (member gender, user type, and bike_share_for_all_trip), two string columns (Start station name and end station name). However, three columns have been changed from numerical to string which are (start_station_id, end_station_id, and bike_id).
    • The dataset has different columns with different missing values count, 197 and 8265. The 197 missing values occured with the station name and ID columns, while the 8265 missing values took place with inforrmation about the member's gender and age.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

  • The main feature of interest is the duration of trip. It is the main feature of which all other features might be involved in predicting it. ### What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest? I speculate that there might be a relationship between the duration of the trip and the following: some features will be constructed from the given data.
  • Age/Age groups of the users. New categorical feature
  • Type of User.
  • User's Gender.
  • Time of day at which the trip started. New categorical feature
  • Time of day at whih the trip ended. New categorical feature
  • Days of the month for both start and end time. New numerical feature

In [19]:
# helper function
def MidNight_to_Night (x):
    if x == 'MidNight':
        return 'Night'
    else:
        return x
FordGoBike.Start_time_day = FordGoBike.Start_time_day.apply(lambda x: MidNight_to_Night(x))
In [20]:
# Add end times of day column 
FordGoBike.loc[:,'End_time_day'] = pd.cut(FordGoBike['end_hour'], bins = [-1,6,12,18,21,23], labels = ['Night', 'Morning', 'Afternoon', 'Evening','MidNight'] )
FordGoBike.End_time_day = FordGoBike.End_time_day.apply(lambda x: MidNight_to_Night(x))

def line_plot (parameter, title, xlabel, ylabel, legend,fig_size = [8,5]):
    plt.figure(figsize = fig_size); 
    plt.plot(parameter, label = legend);
    plt.xlabel(xlabel);
    plt.ylabel(ylabel);
    plt.title(title);
    plt.legend();
    plt.show()
def ShowTwoVariable_lineplot (parameter1,parameter2, title, xlabel, ylabel, legend1,legend2,fig_size = [8,5]):
    plt.figure(figsize = fig_size); 
    plt.plot(parameter1, label = legend1);
    plt.plot(parameter2, label = legend2);
    plt.xlabel(xlabel);
    plt.ylabel(ylabel);
    plt.title(title);
    plt.legend();
    plt.show()
def Plot_Distribution (parameter,title, xlabel, ylabel, legend, fig_size = [8,5]):
    plt.figure(figsize = fig_size); 
    sns.distplot(parameter, label = legend);
    plt.xlabel (xlabel);
    plt.ylabel(ylabel);
    plt.title(title);
    plt.legend();
    plt.show()
def Plot_Hist (parameter,axis,title = None, xlabel = None, ylabel = None, legend = None,minimum = 0, maximum = 0, step = 0, fig_size = [8,5],r_width = 0.7,vis_x= True,vis_y = True,vis_legend = True):
    plt.figure(figsize = fig_size); 
    bins = np.arange(minimum, maximum, step)
    plt.hist(parameter, label = legend, bins = bins, rwidth = r_width);
    plt.title(title);
    plt.xlabel (xlabel).set_visible(vis_x);
    plt.ylabel (ylabel).set_visible(vis_y);
    plt.legend().set_visible(vis_legend);
    plt.axis(axis);
def Plot_HistLog (parameter,axis,title = None, xlabel = None, ylabel = None, legend = None,minimum = 0, maximum = 0, step = 0, fig_size = [8,5],r_width = 0.7,vis_x= True,vis_y = True,vis_legend = True):
    plt.figure(figsize = fig_size); 
    bins = 10 **np.arange(minimum, np.log10(maximum)+step , step)
    plt.hist(parameter, label = legend, bins = bins, rwidth = r_width);
    plt.title(title);
    plt.xlabel (xlabel).set_visible(vis_x);
    plt.ylabel (ylabel).set_visible(vis_y);
    plt.legend().set_visible(vis_legend);
    plt.xscale('log')
    plt.axis(axis);
def Plot_Count (parameter,title, xlabel, ylabel, legend, fig_size = [8,5]):
    plt.figure(figsize = fig_size);
    color_base = sns.color_palette()[0]
    sns.countplot(x = parameter, color = color_base, label = legend);
    plt.title(title);
    plt.xlabel (xlabel);
    plt.ylabel (ylabel);
    plt.legend();
    plt.show()
def Plot_bar (parameter1, parameter2, xlabel,ylabel,title,Rotation = 90):
    plt.figure(figsize = [15, 5]) 
    plt.bar(parameter1,parameter2)
    plt.xlabel(xlabel)
    plt.ylabel(ylabel)
    plt.title(title);
    plt.xticks(rotation = Rotation)
    plt.show()
def Plot_barProp (parameter1, parameter2,Total_count, counts, xlabel,ylabel,title,fig_size = [8, 5],Rotation = 90):
    # rcParams['figure.figsize'] = 12,4
    plt.figure(figsize = fig_size) 
    plt.bar(parameter1,parameter2)
    plt.xlabel(xlabel)
    plt.ylabel(ylabel)
    plt.title(title);
    locs, labels = plt.xticks(rotation=Rotation) 
    # loop through each pair of locations and labels
    for loc, label in zip(locs, labels):
        #count = counts[i]
        # Convert count into a percentage, and then into string
        pct_string = '{:0.1f}%'.format(100*count/Total_count)
        # Print the string value on the bar. 
        # Read more about the arguments of text() function [here](https://matplotlib.org/3.1.1/api/_as_gen/matplotlib.pyplot.text.html)
        plt.text(loc, labels, pct_string, va='center', ha = 'center')

Time and date features are castly siginificant with bike trips in general. That is because in case of months, it is expected to have lower tendancy of riding bikes in winter season, and the exact opposite in summer. Similarly, as shown in the previous graphs, people tend to ride bikes more often in the early hours of the day. However, the dataset has just two months in common (february and march). THerefore, we can't perform any analysis related to the weather conditions. Yet, we might be interested to take a look of the days frequency in the dataset, as by any chance they might dilever some information.

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

The trips duraion are originally in seconds, the quantative variable was plotted by a histogram with a binwidth of 514 seconds. The histogram showed an extremely right skewed distribution with a very long tail. THerefore, the data was re-plotted on a log-scale , at which the distribution was much clearer. The log-scale histogram showed a right skewed distribution as most of the trips had a duration between 0 to 2000 seconds. I had to transform the data from seconds to minnute to have a better and more obvious interpretation of the desired variable. Similarly, the duration in muinutes showed a right skewed distribution, as most of the trips take place between 5 to 15 minutes.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

As discussed earlier, I anticipated that some features of the data will be relatively connected to the main variable of interest (trip duration), which are:

  • Age/ Age groups: I had to transform the member birth year to two newly constructed features, the first is the member age (numerical), and the second is the age group of the member(categorical). This led to better visualization, and more intuitive interperetation. The Age groups column showed higher frequency for younger ages, and the frequency decrease as the age increases.
  • Type of user: I changed this feature to be of a ctegory type. The univariate visualization of this feature showed a signficant superiority of subscribers in terms of trips count.
  • Member's gender: Similar to the type of user, I changed this feature to be categorical type. It is visualization showed a very high frequency of male users, while the female group were only one third of the male groups' count. On the coontrary, the others group had no significant count.
  • Time of day (start/end): This is a newly constructed feature from the trip start time/ end time features. I used the mentioned features to categorize the times of day at which the trips took place. This was to know if a time of day has more trips than the other times, whih can be related to the crowd or the weather. From the visualization of this feature, I found that most of the users tended to have their trips between 6 am to 6 pm.
  • Days of the month: This feature was also constructed from the start/end time features. Yet, its visualization showed no significant conclusion.

Bivariate Exploration¶

Let's first specify the numeric/categorical features of interest in two separate lists.

In [35]:
numeric_vars = ['duration_mins', 'age', 'start_day', 'start_hour']
categoric_vars = ['Start_time_day', 'Age_groups', 'user_type','member_gender','bike_share_for_all_trip']

In the dataset some features have both numeric and categroical representation such as:

  • Age (numeric) - Age Group (Categorical)
  • Start_hour (numeric) - time of day (categorical) Only start day has a numeric representation and no categorical one. Let's first analyze the correlation between each of the numeric variables with the trip duration in mminutes using heat map.
In [36]:
plt.figure(figsize = [8, 5])
sns.heatmap(FordGoBike[numeric_vars].corr(), annot = True, fmt = '.3f',
           cmap = 'vlag_r', center = 0)
plt.show()

The shown heatmap illustrates the linear correlation between each of the numeric variable and the others, including the variable of interest (duration in minutes). Unexpectedly, none of the numeric variables has a linear correlation with the trip duration. Nevertheless, they all have a very weak relationship.

Despite the given heatmap, it will be also important to visualize the scatter plots of the numerical variables against the duration in mins. As in some occasions, there might not be a linear correlation, but a significant relationsfhip appears in the plots. As shown in the univariate distribution, most of the durations were less than 50 mins. Hence, the bivariate distribution will be performed on the data lower than 60 mins for clarity.

In [37]:
samples = np.random.choice(FordGoBike.shape[0], 500, replace = False)
FordGoBike_samp = FordGoBike.loc[samples,:]
first_quartile = FordGoBike_samp.duration_mins >  FordGoBike_samp.duration_mins.quantile(0.25)
second_quartile = FordGoBike_samp.duration_mins < FordGoBike_samp.duration_mins.quantile(0.75)
one_hour_duration = FordGoBike_samp.duration_mins < 50
g = sns.PairGrid(data = FordGoBike_samp[one_hour_duration ], vars = numeric_vars)
g = g.map_diag(plt.hist, bins = 20);
g.map_offdiag(plt.scatter);

The figure above shows the scatter plot for all numeric values against the trips duration in minutes. It is clearly obvious that there is no any linear relationship between any of the features and the main variable of interest. However, we can say that with lower age the chances of having longer trip duration is higher. However, as in the univariate analysis, the days didn't have any obvious relationship with the trip duration, they all havesimilar chances. Similarly, the hours don't have clear relationship with the trip duration except in the night before sunrise, where there are no trips at all. I would like to investigate more the age feature vs. the trips duration using a heatmap.

The next step is to investigate the relationship between the categorical features and the trip duration. This multivariate analysis will take place using boxplots.

In [38]:
samples = np.random.choice(FordGoBike.shape[0], 2000, replace = False)
FordGoBike_samp = FordGoBike.loc[samples,:]
one_hour_duration = FordGoBike_samp.duration_mins < 50

def boxgrid(x, y, **kwargs):
    """ Quick hack for creating box plots with seaborn's PairGrid. """
    default_color = sns.color_palette()[0]
    sns.boxplot(x, y, color = default_color)

plt.figure(figsize = [10, 10]);
g = sns.PairGrid(data = FordGoBike_samp[one_hour_duration ], y_vars = ['duration_mins'], x_vars = categoric_vars,
                size = 3, aspect = 1.5);
g.map(boxgrid);
# plt.ylim([-10, 40]);
plt.show();

<Figure size 720x720 with 0 Axes>

From the boxplots we can see that some expected relationships weren't correctly anticipated, as some features don't have an affect at all.

  • Time of the day: It is shown that the morning and afternoon times have higher maximum trip duration. Yet, there medians and quartiles are so close to the night time at approximately 10 minutes. However, the evening time is slightly lower in the whole measures.
  • Age groups: Similar to the time of the day feature, the three groups had medians lying around 10 minutes duration.
  • User type: Despite the count of subscribers is much higher in the univariate analysis, the customers have more trip durations than them.
  • Memeber gender: they are all so close to each other. Yet, the male group doesn't have a superiority here, as the female group leads slightly in the measures of spread.
  • Bike share condition: they both are very similar to each other without any siginificant coclusion.

From the above box plots, I would like to take a closer look of the user type and memeber gender features using violin plot.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

It was previously expected that the ages will have significant and strong relationship with the trip duration. However, both numerical and categorical age features didn't show a clear relationship with the trip duration. Similarly, the member gender feature didn't have a strong correlation with the trip duration as well. However, the user type showed longer trip duration for customers than subscribers. This can be explained that the subscribers are mainly dependant on the GoBike service on their daily commutes, while the customers don't stick to constant trips and they ride for random destinations.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?¶

There is no any interesting relationship between any other feature and the main variable of interest.
